<subSubSection id="C36665161757AB61FCAE662F9D9A19D4" pageId="18" pageNumber="640" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8BC3369D1757AB61FCAE662F9B1B1DB6" blockId="18.[826,1441,589,733]" pageId="18" pageNumber="640">
<emphasis id="B908EA8F1757AB61FCAE662F9DE11DEA" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="640">
Original diagnosis (
<bibRefCitation id="EFED4B6C1757AB61FBB0662F9B151D08" author="De Bruijn H" box="[1060,1310,589,610]" pageId="18" pageNumber="640" pagination="189 - 373" refId="ref17241" refString="De Bruijn H. 1967. Gliridae, Sciuridae y Eomyidae (Rodentia, Mammalia) miocenos de Calatayud (provincia de Zaragoza, Espana) y su relacion con la bioestratigrafia del area. Boletin del Instituto Geologico y Minero de Espana 78: 189 - 373." type="journal article" year="1967">De Bruijn, 1967: 259</bibRefCitation>
, translated from Spanish):
</emphasis>
‘[Large 
<taxonomicName id="4C7C4D1E1757AB61FBC266099B0D1DEA" authorityName="De Bruijn" authorityYear="1966" box="[1110,1286,619,640]" class="Mammalia" family="Gliridae" genus="Pseudodryomys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="18" pageNumber="640" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B908EA8F1757AB61FBC266099B0D1DEA" box="[1110,1286,619,640]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="640">Pseudodryomys</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with simple dental pattern. The upper molars have neither centrolophs nor extra ridges. The m1 and m2 have a small centrolophid. The m3 is reduced]’.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC3369D1757AB61FCAE67659B621CFC" blockId="18.[826,1441,774,919]" pageId="18" pageNumber="640">
<emphasis id="B908EA8F1757AB61FCAE67659BAA1C71" box="[826,1441,774,796]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="640">
Emended diagnosis by 
<bibRefCitation id="EFED4B6C1757AB61FB0467659B901C71" author="Daams R" box="[1168,1435,774,796]" pageId="18" pageNumber="640" pagination="201 - 240" refId="ref16515" refString="Daams R. 1974. Pseudodryomys (Gliridae, Rodentia, Mammalia) from Early and Middle Miocene deposits in Spain. Proceedings of the Koninklijke Nederlandse Akademie van Wetenschappen Series B 77: 201 - 240." type="journal article" year="1974">Daams (1974: 236)</bibRefCitation>
:
</emphasis>
‘ 
<taxonomicName id="4C7C4D1E1757AB61FCAB67479DE41C50" authorityName="De Bruijn" authorityYear="1966" box="[831,1007,805,826]" class="Mammalia" family="Gliridae" genus="Pseudodryomys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="18" pageNumber="640" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B908EA8F1757AB61FCAB67479DE41C50" box="[831,1007,805,826]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="640">Pseudodryomys</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
-assemblages consisting of large teeth which differ from 
<taxonomicName id="4C7C4D1E1757AB61FB8667269ACB1C33" baseAuthorityName="De Bruijn" baseAuthorityYear="1966" box="[1042,1216,836,857]" class="Mammalia" family="Gliridae" genus="Simplomys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="18" pageNumber="640" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="simplicidens">
<emphasis id="B908EA8F1757AB61FB8667269ACB1C33" box="[1042,1216,836,857]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="640">P. simplicidens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in size and in the less reduced m3. The dental patterns of the other molars are identical of those of 
<taxonomicName id="4C7C4D1E1757AB61FB2567E09B561CFC" baseAuthorityName="De Bruijn" baseAuthorityYear="1966" box="[1201,1373,897,919]" class="Mammalia" family="Gliridae" genus="Simplomys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="18" pageNumber="640" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="simplicidens">
<emphasis id="B908EA8F1757AB61FB2567E09B561CFC" box="[1201,1373,897,919]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="640">P. simplicidens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
’.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC3369D1757AB61FCAE67A29AEB1BC7" blockId="18.[826,1442,960,1197]" pageId="18" pageNumber="640">
<emphasis id="B908EA8F1757AB61FCAE67A29A2F1CBF" box="[826,1060,960,981]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="640">Emended diagnosis:</emphasis>
Large 
<taxonomicName id="4C7C4D1E1757AB61FBEB67A29AF61CBF" authorityName="García-Paredes &amp; Peláez-Campomanes &amp; Álvarez-Sierra" authorityYear="2009" box="[1151,1277,960,981]" class="Mammalia" family="Gliridae" genus="Simplomys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="18" pageNumber="640" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B908EA8F1757AB61FBEB67A29AF61CBF" box="[1151,1277,960,981]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="640">Simplomys</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in which the dental pattern in m1 and m2 is formed by the four main ridges and a well-developed centrolophid. The latter extends diagonally into the central valley but never exceeds the middle part of the occlusal surface. The m3 always has a posterior valley and shows little reduction in its posterior part. The M1 may rarely present a small anterior centroloph.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC3369D1757AB61FCAE60B49A741AC9" blockId="18.[826,1441,1238,1444]" pageId="18" pageNumber="640">
<emphasis id="B908EA8F1757AB61FCAE60B49B4C1B81" box="[826,1351,1238,1259]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="640">
Differential diagnosis: 
<taxonomicName id="4C7C4D1E1757AB61FBC060B49B4C1B81" baseAuthorityName="De Bruijn" baseAuthorityYear="1967" box="[1108,1351,1238,1259]" class="Mammalia" family="Gliridae" genus="Simplomys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="18" pageNumber="640" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="robustus">Simplomys robustus</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
differs from 
<taxonomicName id="4C7C4D1E1757AB61FCE360979A2F1A60" baseAuthorityName="De Bruijn" baseAuthorityYear="1966" box="[887,1060,1269,1290]" class="Mammalia" family="Gliridae" genus="Simplomys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="18" pageNumber="640" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="simplicidens">
<emphasis id="B908EA8F1757AB61FCE360979A2F1A60" box="[887,1060,1269,1290]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="640">S. simplicidens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by having the premolars and the m3 less reduced in size and less simplified in morphology. The posterior valley of m3 is, in contrast to 
<taxonomicName id="4C7C4D1E1757AB61FCAE61339DE61A0C" baseAuthorityName="De Bruijn" baseAuthorityYear="1966" box="[826,1005,1361,1382]" class="Mammalia" family="Gliridae" genus="Simplomys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="18" pageNumber="640" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="simplicidens">
<emphasis id="B908EA8F1757AB61FCAE61339DE61A0C" box="[826,1005,1361,1382]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="640">S. simplicidens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, always present. When both species occur in the same assemblage, 
<taxonomicName id="4C7C4D1E1757AB61FB3D61129B271AEE" baseAuthorityName="De Bruijn" baseAuthorityYear="1967" box="[1193,1324,1391,1413]" class="Mammalia" family="Gliridae" genus="Simplomys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="18" pageNumber="640" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="robustus">
<emphasis id="B908EA8F1757AB61FB3D61129B271AEE" box="[1193,1324,1391,1413]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="640">S. robustus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is always larger than 
<taxonomicName id="4C7C4D1E1757AB61FC5C61EC9A731AC9" baseAuthorityName="De Bruijn" baseAuthorityYear="1966" box="[968,1144,1422,1443]" class="Mammalia" family="Gliridae" genus="Simplomys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="18" pageNumber="640" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="simplicidens">
<emphasis id="B908EA8F1757AB61FC5C61EC9A731AC9" box="[968,1144,1422,1443]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="640">S. simplicidens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
